RABIES, HUMAN, PET EXPOSURE - USA (TENNESSEE, WEST VIRGINIA)
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1] Tennessee
Date: 7 Mar 2007
Source: Times News [edited]
<http://www.timesnews.net/article.php?id=9005450>


Officials confirm rabies throughout Sullivan County, urge owners to
keep animals vaccinated
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Officials with the Sullivan County Regional Health Department are
asking all pet owners to make sure their pets are current on rabies
vaccinations after a raccoon recovered in the Bluff City area tested
positive for rabies.

"There have now been confirmed cases of animal rabies throughout
Sullivan County," Dr. Stephen May, regional medical director for the
Sullivan County Regional Health Department, said. "These cases
highlight the importance of making sure your pets are current on
their rabies vaccinations."

Health department officials said 2 adult dogs and 3 puppies were
exposed to the rabid raccoon at a residence in Bluff City. None of
dogs were current on their rabies vaccination. Health department
officials have recommended that all 5 dogs be euthanized in
accordance with Centers for Disease Control (CDC) guidelines.

They said the only other option for non-vaccinated pets bitten by or
exposed to a rabid animal is to be placed in strict isolation for 6
months. This is done for protection for the animals as well as their
owners and others with whom they may come in contact.

Tennessee law requires that all dogs and cats be vaccinated against
rabies and their shots be kept up to date.

Rabies is a viral disease of mammals that affects the central nervous
system and if left untreated, ultimately results in death.

According to the CDC, more than 90 percent of rabies cases occur in
wildlife such as raccoons, skunks, foxes, and bats. Domestic animals
account for less than 10 percent of rabies cases. Most often reported
domestic rabies cases include cats, dogs, and cattle.

[Byline: Rick Hill Mercedes]

